Yet the judiciary does not simply acquiesce. A federal judge in Maryland temporarily halts \'c1brego\'92s deportation, orders that he remain within reach of the court, and later extends the bar on removal while scheduling an evidentiary hearing and demanding testimony from administration officials. Another judge orders the closure of the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 detention facility in the Florida Everglades within sixty days, citing environmental and human rights violations, and denies a motion to stay the order. In Washington, a grand jury refuses to indict a protester accused of throwing a sandwich at a federal officer during demonstrations against the troop presence, an act widely read as a small but pointed rebuke to the militarization of the city. A federal judge dismisses the administration\'92s extraordinary lawsuit against all fifteen judges of Maryland\'92s federal district court, reaffirming judicial immunity and criticizing the executive for bypassing normal appeals. These rulings do not reverse the broader trend of law being used as a weapon, but they show that some judges still see their role as a limit on power rather than its instrument. That distinction still matters.\
