A third development lies in the politicization and capture of technocratic institutions, especially in public health and monetary policy. At the Federal Reserve, the president first threatens and then announces the removal of governor Lisa Cook, the first Black woman to serve in that role, citing unproven mortgage fraud allegations. The Federal Reserve Act allows removal only \'93for cause,\'94 and Cook insists that the president lacks legal authority to fire her and that she will continue her duties. Her lawyers prepare to contest the dismissal in court. The episode is part of a broader pattern in which independent economic bodies are treated as extensions of the executive, their statutory protections tested by unilateral acts and public smears. The same week, the administration touts a ten percent government stake in Intel, negotiated directly with the company\'92s chief executive, and floats the idea of taking similar stakes in other major contractors. Critics on the right call it socialism, but the deeper concern is crony capitalism: when the state becomes both regulator and shareholder, corporate fortunes depend on presidential favor, and policy outcomes are shaped in private meetings rather than in open deliberation.\
\
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention experience an even more direct purge. Susan Monarez, a Senate\uc0\u8209 confirmed director and infectious disease expert, is fired after only weeks in office. Her lawyers argue that only the president can remove her and that the Department of Health and Human Services acted improperly. Reports indicate that she refused to change coronavirus vaccine guidelines without consulting scientific advisers and resisted directives she considered reckless and unscientific. In the wake of her ouster, four senior CDC officials resign: the chief medical officer, the head of infectious diseases, and other key leaders. One resignation letter cites manipulation of data for political ends and a lack of transparency. The administration then appoints Jim O\'92Neill, a biotech investor and ally of the anti\u8209 vaccine health secretary, as acting CDC head. O\'92Neill has no medical or scientific training but is expected to support efforts to remake vaccine policy. At the same time, confusing new restrictions on Covid vaccines are announced, with contradictory statements about eligibility and access. The combined effect is to turn a scientific agency into a political arm, to drive out those who insist on evidence\u8209 based practice, and to leave the public facing muddled guidance in the midst of a health crisis. Public trust erodes in that fog.\
