The civil service more broadly comes under pressure when it resists or exposes mismanagement. At FEMA, 182 employees sign a \'93Katrina Declaration\'94 letter to Congress, warning that one\uc0\u8209 third of the agency\'92s full\u8209 time staff have left, that institutional knowledge is eroding, and that budget cuts and inexperience could lead to disaster response failures reminiscent of Hurricane Katrina. Shortly after, about thirty of the signatories are placed on administrative leave. The message is clear: those who speak candidly about risk and capacity may find themselves sidelined. A whistleblower at the Department of Government Efficiency reports that a former senior official copied Social Security data for more than 300 million Americans to an unsecured cloud server, in apparent violation of law and basic data security. That disclosure underscores how much sensitive information the state holds and how fragile its safeguards can be. Together with the CDC resignations and the treatment of FEMA staff, these events show a civil service in which loyalty and silence are rewarded, and expertise or candor can be liabilities. The cost is borne in future crises.\
\
A fourth development is the deliberate reshaping of the economic order in ways that favor insiders and increase dependence among workers. The government\'92s stake in Intel is the most visible symbol of a new industrial policy, but it is accompanied by a series of decisions that weaken labor protections and shift risk onto those with the least bargaining power. The administration proposes a rule to eliminate federal minimum wage and overtime protections for 3.7 million childcare and home care workers, sectors dominated by women and people of color. It rescinds a minimum wage requirement for disabled workers, reopening the door to subminimum pay in sheltered workshops and other settings. It cuts the minimum wage for federal contractors from $17.75 to $13.30 an hour, reducing earnings for a large class of workers who often provide public services. It issues an executive order excluding additional federal units from the labor\uc0\u8209 management relations program, and separately attempts to strip collective bargaining rights from about one million federal employees, an act described as the largest single union\u8209 busting move in U.S. history. These measures do not simply save money. They erode the capacity of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to resist arbitrary treatment, leaving them more atomized and dependent on employers and the state.\
