Trade and tariff policy add another layer to this economic shift. The administration removes the de minimis exemption that allowed packages under $800 to enter the country without tariffs. Postal services in nearly thirty countries suspend deliveries to the United States as they adjust to the new rules, and small businesses that rely on low\uc0\u8209 value imports face higher costs and delays. An executive order ending the exemption is expected to impose up to $13 billion in additional costs, hitting consumers and small firms that use direct\u8209 to\u8209 consumer models. The White House justifies the move as a defense of American manufacturers and national security, but the burden falls most heavily on lower\u8209 income households and small entrepreneurs. At the same time, the administration cancels solar and wind projects funded under the CHIPS Act, favoring fossil fuels and undermining long\u8209 term job creation in clean energy. It cuts $1.1 billion from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, weakening a public information infrastructure that is especially important in rural areas for severe weather alerts. These choices reinforce a pattern in which economic pain for the less powerful is an accepted tool of policy, while favored firms and sectors receive direct attention and, in Intel\'92s case, state investment.\
\
A fifth development concerns the manipulation of representation and the rules of political competition. In Texas, the governor signs a new congressional map that could raise Republican seats from twenty\uc0\u8209 five to thirty out of thirty\u8209 eight, despite the state\'92s demographic diversity. Civil rights groups sue, arguing that the map is a racial gerrymander that strips Black voters of their political power and violates the Voting Rights Act. In Missouri, the governor calls a special legislative session to redraw congressional districts in a way expected to add another Republican seat, and to consider changes to the initiative process that would make citizen\u8209 led measures harder to pass. At the national level, the president announces that lawyers are drafting an executive order to eliminate mail\u8209 in balloting, a method used by nearly a third of Americans and not credibly linked to fraud. The idea arises after a conversation with the Russian president, who claims that mail\u8209 in voting cost Trump the 2020 election. The administration also plans to sue California to block its mid\u8209 decade redistricting, which is designed to counterbalance gains from Texas\'92s map. These moves, taken together, show a governing project that seeks to shape who votes, how votes are cast, and how those votes are translated into seats, often under the banner of \'93integrity\'94 but with clear partisan aims.\
