Here, too, there is resistance. A Utah judge orders the state to redraw its congressional map before the 2026 midterms, ruling that the Republican\uc0\u8209 drawn plan violated a 2018 initiative establishing an independent redistricting commission. The current map splits Salt Lake City across all four districts, diluting its Democratic vote; the court\'92s decision requires lawmakers to comply with voter\u8209 approved standards and could make at least one seat more competitive. In Georgia, Democrat Debra Shigley leads a special state senate race in a traditionally Republican district, forcing a runoff, while in Iowa Democrat Catelin Drey flips a state senate seat that Trump had carried by more than eleven points. These electoral outcomes do not undo the structural advantages built into maps and voting rules, but they show that voters can still shift the balance when given a fair chance. They also suggest that efforts to lock in minority rule through redistricting and restrictions on mail\u8209 in voting are responses to a changing electorate, not expressions of confidence. The ground is moving under the maps.\
