A sixth development is the tightening of control over protest and expression, both through law and through force. The president signs and promotes a series of executive orders directing the Department of Justice to prioritize prosecutions for burning the American flag, despite Supreme Court precedent protecting such acts as speech. Some versions of the order emphasize cases where flag burning is linked to violence or property damage; others, including the president\'92s own statements, speak of a mandatory one\uc0\u8209 year prison sentence for any desecration. The orders also instruct agencies to deny immigration benefits to foreign nationals involved in flag burning. These measures do not yet overturn the Court\'92s ruling, but they invite prosecutors to test the boundaries and send a signal that a core protest act is now a target. At the same time, the administration moves to end cashless bail in Washington, D.C., and in other jurisdictions by threatening to cut federal funds. Cashless bail reforms were designed to reduce pretrial detention for poor defendants without increasing crime; the orders frame them as drivers of violence and direct federal law enforcement to hold arrestees in custody to the fullest extent possible. The combined effect is to expand the state\'92s power to detain and to criminalize dissent, especially in cities already under heavy federal presence.\
