On the ground, these legal shifts are reinforced by security deployments. In Washington, D.C., the National Guard and Immigration and Customs Enforcement operate side by side, creating a climate of fear among immigrant communities. Restaurant workers, many of them immigrants, stay home to avoid potential raids, and businesses close or cut hours. In Chicago and other cities, the prospect of Guard deployments hangs over local politics, with governors urging peaceful protest but warning that the president is using troops to intimidate rivals rather than to address crime. Civil society responds with its own language and actions. Indivisible issues a statement titled \'93The Militarization of American Cities is Underway, Started with DC,\'94 arguing that federal control of policing in majority\uc0\u8209 Black cities is racially motivated and undermines local governance. Organizers plan a march in Washington on September 6 to demand the withdrawal of federal troops, starting in Malcolm X Park, and a Labor Day die\u8209 in in Raleigh to dramatize the human costs of a sweeping federal bill. These acts of protest show that the right to assemble and speak has not been extinguished, but they now take place in a landscape where executive orders, armed troops, and politicized prosecutions are part of the backdrop. The streets themselves tell that story.\
