A seventh development concerns the curation of memory and symbols by those in power. The president issues an executive order titled \'93Making Federal Architecture Beautiful Again,\'94 mandating that new federal buildings, especially in Washington, use classical and traditional styles unless exceptional circumstances justify otherwise. The order criticizes modernist and brutalist designs and calls for architecture that reflects the dignity of the American government and inspires civic virtue. At the same time, the General Services Administration revises its Art\uc0\u8209 in\u8209 Architecture program to prioritize works that depict historically significant Americans and events, in line with recent executive directives. These choices might seem aesthetic, but they shape the visual language of the state and the stories it tells about itself. In the military sphere, the Pentagon announces that it will restore a portrait of Confederate general Robert E. Lee to the library at West Point, even though a 2020 law required the removal of Confederate tributes from military installations. The painting shows Lee with an enslaved man. Its return, championed by the administration and the defense secretary, signals a willingness to override or reinterpret prior democratic decisions about which symbols belong in public institutions. Memory, in this account, is not a neutral record but a field of contest in which those in power decide which histories are honored and which are sidelined.\
