Amid these shifts, there are also developments that strengthen transparency and technical governance, though they do not alter the week\'92s overall direction. The National Archives schedules a Freedom of Information Act advisory committee meeting to discuss vexatious requests and subcommittee recommendations, keeping alive a forum for improving access to records. The Election Assistance Commission announces a public meeting of its Technical Guidelines Development Committee to discuss updates to voting system standards, with a livestream to allow public observation. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, even as its leadership is purged, proposes a standardized data management plan template and schedules a meeting of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices to consider vaccine recommendations in an open, virtual format. The Federal Communications Commission and the Environmental Protection Agency seek public comment on various information collections and rules, from accessibility of digital devices to economic focus groups and pesticide labeling. These processes show that parts of the administrative state continue to function in a rule\uc0\u8209 bound, participatory way. They are, however, overshadowed by the more visible acts of executive assertion and institutional capture. The contrast is stark.\
