\
In the larger arc of the term, Week 32 matters less for any single headline than for the way its pieces fit together. The Democracy Clock\'92s time at 7:57 p.m. captures a system that still has functioning courts, elections, and civil society, but in which the balance of power is tilting steadily toward an executive that sees oversight as an obstacle, not a duty. The week\'92s small forward movement reflects the normalization of emergency powers in domestic governance, the use of law enforcement and regulatory data to target opponents, the purging and politicizing of expert institutions, and the deliberate weakening of labor protections that once gave workers some leverage against both state and corporate power. At the same time, judges in Utah, Maryland, and Florida, governors in California and Illinois, and organizers in cities across the country show that resistance is possible and sometimes effective. The question the Clock poses is not whether democracy still exists, but how much longer it can absorb such pressures without a more visible break. Week 32 closes with the official time unchanged, but with the sense that the evening is growing denser, and that each new \'93emergency,\'94 each new exception, makes it harder to return to a daylight politics of shared rules and mutual restraint.\
